s":"Welshpool, Montgomeryshire, Wales, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"about 1230–AFT    1315":"about 1230–after 1315","1230–1315":"1230–1315","–Male":"Deceased","1234–Female":"1234–Deceased","1236–Female":"1236–Deceased","1254–Female":"1254–Deceased","1256–Male":"1256–Deceased","1205–Male":"1205–Deceased","1209–Female":"1209–Deceased","1205":"1205","1315":"1315","1236":"1236","ABT    1254":"about 1254","1256":"1256","1234":"1234","1254":"1254","AFT    1315":"after 1315","1230":"1230","about 1256":"about 1256","1209":"1209","about 1230":"about 1230","of Bers,Wrexham,Denbighshire,Wales":"Denbighshire, Wales, United Kingdom","of,Tegeingl ctf,Flintshire,Wales":"Flintshire, Wales","{Blddn ap Cnfn}":"Ascoli Piceno, Marche, Italy","Llanfair Dyffryn Clwyd, Denbighshire, Wales":"Llanfair Dyffryn Clwyd, Denbighshire, Wales","of Llannerch Hud,Welshpool,Montgomeryshire,Wales":"Welshpool, Montgomeryshire, Wales, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"\"Gôch\"","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From Italian <b>Rocco</b>; ."],"variants":[]},{"name":"ap","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of any of the names beginning with this syllable."],"variants":[{"name":"Alexander","meanings":["From the Latin form of the Greek name <i>Alexandros</i>, from <i>alexein</i> ‘to defend’ + <i>anēr</i> ‘man, warrior’ (genitive <i>andros</i>). The name became extremely popular in the post-classical period, and was borne by several individuals in the New Testament and some early Christian saints. Its use as a common given name throughout Europe, however, derives largely from the fame of  Alexander the Great , King of Macedon (  356–323  bc  ), around whom a large body of popular legend grew up in late antiquity, much of which came to be embodied in the medieval ‘Alexander romances’."]},{"name":"Alan","meanings":["Of Celtic origin and uncertain derivation (possibly a diminutive of a word meaning ‘rock’). It was introduced into England by  Breton  followers of  William the Conqueror , most notably  Alan , Earl of Brittany, who was rewarded for his services with vast estates in the newly conquered kingdom. In Britain the variants  <b>Allan</b>  and  <b>Allen</b>  are considerably less frequent, and generally represent transferred uses of surname forms, whereas in America all three forms of the name are approximately equally common.  See also  Alun ."]},{"name":"Albert","meanings":["From an Old French name, <i>Albert</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to England, displacing the Old English form <i>Æþelbeorht</i>. The name is popular in a variety of forms in Western Europe, and has been traditional in a number of European princely families. It was out of favour in England for centuries, however, and the revival of its popularity in the 19th century was largely in honour of  Queen Victoria's  consort,  Prince Albert of Saxe-Coburg-Gotha ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Ednyfed \"Gôch\" ap Cynwrig was born about 1230, in Denbighshire, Wales, United Kingdom, his father, Cynwrig, was 27 and his mother, Efa ferch Llywelyn, was 23. He had at least 1 son and 1 daughter with Efa ferch Rhirid. He died after 1315."},"et":{"about 1230–AFT    1315":"umbes 1230–pärast 1315","1230–1315":"1230–1315","–Male":"Surnud","1234–Female":"1234–Surnud","1236–Female":"1236–Surnud","1254–Female":"1254–Surnud","1256–Male":"1256–Surnud","1205–Male":"1205–Surnud","1209–Female":"1209–Surnud","1205":"1205","1315":"1315","1236":"1236","ABT    1254":"umbes 1254","1256":"1256","1234":"1234","1254":"1254","AFT    1315":"pärast 1315","1230":"1230","about 1256":"umbes 1256","1209":"1209","about 1230":"umbes 1230","of Bers,Wrexham,Denbighshire,Wales":"Denbighshire, Wales, United Kingdom","of,Tegeingl ctf,Fl